  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Building Resilient and Sustainable Livelihoods for Smallholder Coconut Farmers</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- Consultation with Community Based Organization (CBO), LGUs, and landowners
- Farm debris clearing and land preparation
- Establishment of demo farm on integrated farming system (IFS)
- Training on Integrated farming system (IFS) and Crop Management
- Distribution of planting materials
- Monitoring, coaching, and mentoring of the adoption of IFS and Crop Management</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Disaster-affected smallholder farmers (men and women)</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will address vulnerability of small holder coconut farmers in Burauen, Kananga, and Jaro brought about by Typhoon Haiyan which displaced thousands of people and damaged their primary source of livelihood. The vulnerability is also due to the dependency of farmers on coconut as livelihood, low-productivity from coconut based-livelihood due to loss of coconut trees, and lack of absorptive and adaptive capacities of communities to the impact of climate change.

The goal is to ensure beneficiaries recover and rebuild their livelihoods in ways to maximize their resilience to future disasters. The project aims to achieve the following: (1) disaster-affected people from Eastern Visayas increase livelihood diversification to improve resilience to shocks and stresses; (2) disaster-affected people from Eastern Visayas increase productivity from primary livelihoods to improve resilience to shocks and stresses; and, (3) communities have improved absorptive and adaptive capacities in livelihood resilience.</narrative>
  </description>
